<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8"?>

<worksheet xml:id="ic3-reading" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>IC-3 Reading</title>
    <objectives>
    <ul>
      <li><p>Things you should understand and know:
        <ul>
            <li>Recognize when a function of three variables is integrable over a rectangular region or a closed and bounded region</li>
            <li>Recognize when changing the order of integration may be needed</li>
            <li>Understand what cylindrical boxes are and how these are used in evaluating triple integrals</li>
            <li>Understand what spherical boxes are and how these are used in evaluating triple integrals</li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>Things you should be able to do:
        <ul>
            <li>Use properties to evaluate triple integrals</li>
            <li>Evaluate a triple integral over a rectangular by writing it as an iterated integral</li>
            <li>Use triple integrals to calculate volumes and average values</li>
            <li>Simplify the calculation of an iterated integral by changing the order of integration</li>
            <li>Evaluate a triple integral by changing to cylindrical coordinates</li>
            <li>Evaluate a triple integral by changing to spherical coordinates</li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
      <li><p>You will be assessed on the following criteria:
        <ul>
          <li><p>Problem structure: Solution should be organized and easy to follow, with clear, complete steps 
              that follow progressively from one to the next.</p></li>
          <li><p>Triple Integrals: Compute triple integrals over rectangular regions. Compute the volumes of 
            solids using triple integrals. Solve applied problems using triple integrals.</p></li>
          <li><p>Triple Integrals in Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates: Compute triple integrals in cylindrical 
            and spherical coordinates. Compute the volumes of solids using triple integrals in cylindrical and 
            spherical coordinates. Solve applied problems using triple integrals in cylindrical and spherical coordinates.</p></li>
        </ul></p>
      </li>
    </ul>
    </objectives>
        <p>All of the readings for this course come from the OpenStax Calculus 
            Volume 3 textbook, which is available for free online at 
            <url href="https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3">
                https://openstax.org/details/books/calculus-volume-3</url>. You 
                can read the textbook online or download a PDF version. 
                The textbook is also available in print from various retailers 
                if you prefer a physical copy.</p> 
        <p>For this lesson, you should read sections <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/5-4-triple-integrals">
            5.4 Triple Integrals</url>, and <url href="https://openstax.org/books/calculus-volume-3/pages/5-5-triple-integrals-in-cylindrical-and-spherical-coordinates">
            5.5 Triple Integrals in Cylindrical and Spherical Coordinates</url>. You should read through the sections carefully, 
            making sure to understand the definitions, examples, and key ideas. 
            You should also work through the exercises at the end of each section 
            to test your understanding and practice applying the concepts. Some of the 
            exercises at the end of the section are assigned in the WP assignments.</p>      
</worksheet>
